IMO, the shared space concept is a flawed one.  Unlike pedestrians,
motorized vehicles cannot stop or change direction &quot;instantaneously.&quot;
This is due to the mass and inertia inherent to a motor vehicle at a
given velocity.  This is also the case for bicyclists.

This is the reason why a set of rules regarding right-of-way are in
place for motor vehicles and other road users when their paths could
possibly cross each other.  Also, pedestrians have plenty of area to
enjoy themselves in.  They're free to run, jog, stroll, or walk however
they please when they're not on the road.  But, in the interest of
safety, they have to follow the rules of the road when they prepare to
cross one.

Addressing points brought up in the Wikipedia article you cited:

1. &quot;User behavior becomes influenced and controlled by natural human
interactions rather than by artificial regulation.&quot;

This only works at walking speeds.  You can't rely on &quot;natural human
interaction&quot; when driving even at 15 mph to avoid collisions.  Also,
this type of interaction requires one not to be insulated from their
surroundings like one would be in a motor vehicle.  Even if one is
riding a bicycle or motorcycle, their speed and reduced maneuverability
relative to pedestrians makes &quot;natural human interaction&quot; an inadequate
measure to prevent collisions.

2. &quot; ... [R]oad rules strip motorists of the ability to be considerate.&quot;

Why is it that we have to rely on motorists being considerate?  Why
can't pedestrians be considerate and wait to cross the road until
vehicular traffic has passed?  Inconsiderate pedestrians are the ones
who step out less than 50 feet in front of a moving vehicle when there
are no other vehicles behind it.  Considerate pedestrians are the ones
who wait for the vehicle to pass.

I believe the main problem is that certain people or groups want to
abrogate the responsibility of pedestrians to watch out for themselves
when they interact with motor vehicle traffic.  Pedestrians have the
duty to make sure that they don't put themselves in a position where
they could get hit by a vehicle.  That requires that they act in a
predictable manner when they're on the road and when they're preparing
to cross the road.  It's no different when driving a motor vehicle (or
riding a bicycle) and preparing to pull out onto the main road from a
side road.  Drivers or riders in that situation aren't going to rely on
&quot;natural human interaction&quot; with drivers of vehicles comprising
traffic on the main road to avoid a collision.  They're going to rely on
the established rules defining right-of-way in those situations.  The
same concept applies to pedestrians.
